    "# Faster-RCNN Model Training Preparation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Introduction\n",
    "\n",
    "The purpose of this notebook is to outline the necessary steps and considerations for preparing to fine-tune a Faster-RCNN model. The goal of such fine-tuning would be to potentially improve human detection performance, especially in the specific context of truck surveillance scenarios. \n",
    "\n",
    "While pre-trained models (e.g., on COCO) provide a strong baseline for general object detection, fine-tuning on a more domain-specific dataset can often lead to better accuracy, reduced false positives/negatives, and improved robustness for the target environment."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Identifying Relevant Datasets\n",
    "\n",
    "The choice of dataset is crucial for successful fine-tuning. Several options exist:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **COCO (Common Objects in Context):**\n",
    "  - Website: [cocodataset.org](https://cocodataset.org/)\n",
    "  - Notes: The Faster-RCNN model we are using is already pre-trained on COCO. For fine-tuning, one might filter COCO for images containing humans in outdoor or vehicle-related settings, or use it as a base for further augmentation with custom data. It's a rich dataset with diverse scenes.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Pascal VOC (Visual Object Classes):**\n",
    "  - Website: [host.robots.ox.ac.uk/pascal/VOC/](http://host.robots.ox.ac.uk/pascal/VOC/)\n",
    "  - Notes: Another foundational object detection dataset. Contains a 'person' category. It's smaller than COCO but still widely used.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **OpenImages:**\n",
    "  - Website: [storage.googleapis.com/openimages/web/index.html](https://storage.googleapis.com/openimages/web/index.html)\n",
    "  - Notes: A very large dataset by Google, with millions of images and bounding box annotations for many classes, including 'Person'. Its size and diversity can be beneficial, but also requires more effort to curate.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Surveillance-Specific Datasets:**\n",
    "  - Examples: \n",
    "    - **PETS (Performance Evaluation of Tracking and Surveillance):** Older, but often used for benchmarking. (Search for specific year's dataset, e.g., PETS2009)\n",
    "    - **VIRAT Video Dataset:** Focuses on activities and events in surveillance video. ([viratdata.org](https://viratdata.org/))\n",
    "  - Notes: These datasets are more aligned with surveillance tasks but can be complex, often involving video sequences, varied camera angles, and potentially requiring significant preprocessing or annotation conversion. Academic search terms: \"human detection in surveillance dataset\", \"person detection outdoor scenes dataset\".\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Custom Data Collection:**\n",
    "  - Notes: This is often the most effective approach for achieving high performance in a specific domain. It involves collecting images or video footage from the actual target environment (e.g., around trucks in various conditions) and annotating them meticulously. This is time-consuming but ensures the model learns features most relevant to the deployment scenario.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Criteria for Dataset Selection:\n",
    "- **Relevance to Task:** How well does the dataset represent the scenarios the model will encounter (e.g., viewing angles, lighting, human poses relevant to truck surveillance)?\n",
    "- **Image Quality:** Resolution, clarity, and diversity of images.\n",
    "- **Annotation Quality:** Accuracy and consistency of bounding box annotations for humans.\n",
    "- **Dataset Size:** Sufficient number of instances of humans and diverse backgrounds.\n",
    "- **Licensing:** Ensure the dataset license permits use for your intended purpose."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Data Exploration and Preprocessing Plan\n",
    "\n",
    "Once a dataset (or a combination) is chosen, several preprocessing steps are necessary:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Annotation Format Consistency:**\n",
    "  - Common formats include COCO JSON (e.g., `{\"images\": [...], \"annotations\": [...], \"categories\": [...]}`), Pascal VOC XML (one XML file per image), and others.\n",
    "  - PyTorch training pipelines typically require a custom dataset class that can read these formats and provide images and targets (bounding boxes, labels) in the expected tensor format.\n",
    "  - Tools like [Roboflow](https://roboflow.com/) or [CVAT](https://github.com/cvat-ai/cvat) can help manage and convert annotation formats.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Data Cleaning:**\n",
    "  - Review a subset of images and annotations to check for errors (e.g., mislabeled objects, inaccurate bounding boxes).\n",
    "  - Check image quality (e.g., excessively blurry, corrupted files) and decide whether to exclude or attempt to fix them.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Class Distribution Analysis:**\n",
    "  - For human detection, the primary class is 'person'. Verify its `category_id` in the chosen dataset.\n",
    "  - If other object classes are present and not needed, they might be ignored or filtered out during data loading to simplify the task (unless a multi-class detector is desired).\n",
    "  - Understand the number of human instances per image and across the dataset to ensure sufficient training examples.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Data Augmentation Strategies:**\n",
    "  - Augmentation artificially increases the diversity of the training set, helping the model generalize better.\n",
    "  - Common techniques for object detection include:\n",
    "    - Geometric transformations: Horizontal flipping (very common for people), scaling, rotation, translation, shearing.\n",
    "    - Photometric transformations: Color jitter (brightness, contrast, saturation, hue adjustments), adding noise.\n",
    "    - Mosaic augmentation, MixUp: Combine parts of multiple images.\n",
    "  - Libraries like Albumentations or torchvision.transforms can be used. Care must be taken to ensure bounding boxes are correctly transformed along with the images."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# PSEUDO-CODE for exploring COCO-style annotations\n",
    "import json\n",
    "\n",
    "def explore_coco_annotations(annotations_path):\n",
    "    try:\n",
    "        with open(annotations_path, 'r') as f:\n",
    "            coco_data = json.load(f)\n",
    "    except FileNotFoundError:\n",
    "        print(f\"Error: Annotation file not found at {annotations_path}\")\n",
    "        return\n",
    "    except json.JSONDecodeError:\n",
    "        print(f\"Error: Could not decode JSON from {annotations_path}\")\n",
    "        return\n",
    "\n",
    "    print(f\"Number of images: {len(coco_data.get('images', []))}\")\n",
    "    print(f\"Number of annotations: {len(coco_data.get('annotations', []))}\")\n",
    "    \n",
    "    categories = coco_data.get('categories', [])\n",
    "    print(f\"Categories: {categories}\")\n",
    "    category_id_to_name = {cat['id']: cat['name'] for cat in categories}\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Example: Count instances per category\n",
    "    category_counts = {}\n",
    "    for ann in coco_data.get('annotations', []):\n",
    "        cat_id = ann.get('category_id')\n",
    "        if cat_id is not None:\n",
    "            cat_name = category_id_to_name.get(cat_id, 'Unknown')\n",
    "            category_counts[cat_name] = category_counts.get(cat_name, 0) + 1\n",
    "    \n",
    "    print(\"Instance counts per category:\")\n",
    "    for name, count in category_counts.items():\n",
    "        print(f\"  - {name}: {count}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Example usage (conceptual):\n",
    "# annotations_file = 'path_to_your_coco_annotations.json'\n",
    "# explore_coco_annotations(annotations_file)"
   ],
   "execution_count": null
  },
