    "## Fine-tuning Strategy for Faster-RCNN (PyTorch)\n",
    "\n",
    "A typical PyTorch fine-tuning script for Faster-RCNN involves these key components:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Dataset Class (`torch.utils.data.Dataset`):**\n",
    "  - A custom class that inherits from `torch.utils.data.Dataset`.\n",
    "  - `__init__`: Initializes with image paths, annotation data, and transforms.\n",
    "  - `__len__`: Returns the total number of samples in the dataset.\n",
    "  - `__getitem__`: Loads an image (e.g., using PIL or OpenCV), retrieves its corresponding annotations (bounding boxes and labels), applies transformations/augmentations, and returns the image and target dictionary (e.g., `{'boxes': tensor_boxes, 'labels': tensor_labels}`).\n",
    "\n",
    "- **DataLoaders (`torch.utils.data.DataLoader`):**\n",
    "  - Wrap the custom Dataset instances for training and validation sets.\n",
    "  - Handle batching, shuffling (for training), and multi-worker data loading.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Model Modification:**\n",
    "  - Load a pre-trained Faster-RCNN model from `torchvision.models.detection` (e.g., `fasterrcnn_resnet50_fpn`).\n",
    "  - **Crucially, replace the classifier head (box predictor) to match the number of classes in your fine-tuning dataset.** If you are only detecting 'person', you need `num_classes = 2` (person + background).\n",
    "  - The `FastRCNNPredictor` class is used for this replacement.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Optimizer:**\n",
    "  - Choose an optimizer, e.g., SGD (Stochastic Gradient Descent) with momentum, or Adam/AdamW.\n",
    "  - Pass the model parameters that require gradients to the optimizer (`model.parameters()`).\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Loss Function:**\n",
    "  - For Faster-RCNN, the loss is a combination of RPN (Region Proposal Network) losses (objectness and bounding box regression) and Fast R-CNN losses (classification and bounding box regression for final proposals).\n",
    "  - When using `torchvision`'s Faster-RCNN model in training mode (`model.train()`), if you pass targets during the forward pass (`model(images, targets)`), the model itself computes and returns a dictionary of losses.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Training Loop:**\n",
    "  - Iterate for a specified number of epochs.\n",
    "  - Within each epoch, iterate through batches from the training DataLoader.\n",
    "  - Move images and targets to the appropriate device (CPU/GPU).\n",
    "  - Perform the forward pass: `loss_dict = model(images, targets)`.\n",
    "  - Combine losses: `losses = sum(loss for loss in loss_dict.values())`.\n",
    "  - Perform backpropagation: `optimizer.zero_grad()`, `losses.backward()`.\n",
    "  - Update model weights: `optimizer.step()`.\n",
    "  - (Optional) Learning rate scheduling.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Evaluation:**\n",
    "  - Periodically, or after training, evaluate the model on a separate validation set.\n",
    "  - Set the model to evaluation mode: `model.eval()`.\n",
    "  - Common metrics for object detection include mAP (mean Average Precision) at various IoU (Intersection over Union) thresholds. Libraries like `pycocotools` can be used for COCO-style evaluation.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Saving Checkpoints:**\n",
    "  - Save the model's state dictionary (`model.state_dict()`) and optimizer state regularly, especially after improvements in validation metrics. This allows resuming training or using the trained model later."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
